stigmatize China. Robyn R. Warhol and Nicholas O. Warner examine accounts of alcohol abuse in texts as disparate as Victorian novels, Alcoholics Anonymous literature, and James Fenimore Cooper's fiction. Helen Keane scrutinizes smoking, and Maurizio Viano turns to the silver screen to trace how the representation of drugs in films has changed over time. Ann Weinstone and Marguerite Waller's essays on addiction and cyberspace cap this impressive anthology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAlcoholism in literature. 0aAlcoholism in motion pictures. 0aAlcoolisme au cinéma. 0aAlcoolisme dans la littérature. 0aDrogues et cinéma. 0aDrogues et littérature. 0aDrugs and literature. 0aDrugs and motion pictures. 0aPolytoxicomaniexAspect social. 0aRéalité virtuellexAspect social. 0aSubstance abusexSocial aspects. 0aVirtual realityxSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aBrodie, Janet, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRedfield, Marc, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520935709423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520935709.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles